18th International Schumpeter Conference / 08-10 July 2021

Covid-19: Health or economy?



President Donald Trump fixed his course on reopening the nation for business, acknowledging that the move would cause more illness and death from the pandemic but insisting its a cost hes willing to pay to get the economy back on track.
Source: Bloomberg, 6 Mays 2020

Topics

  • Is there a trade off between economic and health outcomes?

Microsimulation model

  • Which policies are effective in reducing the spread of Covid-19?
  • What are the costs of these policies in terms of foregone output (value added) and employment?
  • Who are the most effected by these policies?
  • What could the government do to reduce the social and economic cost of Covid-19?

Covid-19 measures

  • Stay-at-home rules (partial/general)
  • Closing down businesses (restaurants, tourism, etc)
  • Restricting certain (mass) activities (conferences, concerts, etc)
  • Travel restrictions (local, national and international)
  • Closing schools/on-line education
  • Others
    • Testing and filiation
    • Masks, social distancing
    • Teleworking

Economic effects of Covid-19 measures

Short run

  • Decline in output and employment
    • Closing down businesses
    • Reducing (consumption) expenditures
      • Uncertainty and restrictions
      • Increasing unemployment
        • Income support
    • Decline in investment
    • Decline in foreign demand (declining exports)

Economic effects of Covid-19 measures

Long term

  • Depreciation of human capital
    • Health problems
    • Problems in education/access to on-line education
    • Increasing youth unemployment
  • Declining investment
  • Changes in consumer behavior
  • Changes in the direction of technological change

Health vs economics

Economic effect: Level x Duration (-) Health effect: Level x Duration (+)

  • Economic effects
    • Decline in value added and employment
    • Policy stringency index
    • Google mobility index
      • Workplace mobility, retail and recreation mobility, etc
  • Health effects
    • Covid-19 deaths
    • Additional deaths
    • Case numbers

The microsimulation model

  • Agents
    • About 500,000 individual representing whole population (about 80 million)
      • The number of unique individual in the model increases to 3-4 million during simulation
    • Household, age, gender, school, sector, occupation, formal/informal, working hours, region
    • 2017 Labor Survey Data
  • Locations
    • Household: Household members
    • School: Students and the education sector employees in a given region (region is defined at NUTS 2-digit level).
    • Workplace: People employed in a given sector and region
    • Essential activities: All people living in a given region and those work in the essential sectors
    • Leisure activities: All people living in a given region and those work in the leisure sectors
    • Travel: All people

Modules

  • Disease progression module
  • Infection module
  • Measures/policies module
  • Production and employment module

Module 1: Disease progression module

Modul 2. Infection

  • Individuals
    • pre-school, school, unemployed women, unemployed men, employed women, employed men
  • Locations
    • home, school, workplace, essential activities, leisure activities, travel
  • Each individual spends 16 hours per day in those locations
  • The number of infected people in a given location in a day depends on
    • Time spent by susceptible people times
    • Time spent by infected people over
    • Time spent by all people (including recovered)
  • In the case of essential and leisure activities, transmission probability depends the degree of contacts with customers [O*Net, Deal With External Customers data]
  • For teleworking, Dingel and Neimans (2020) work-at-home data is used.

Module 3. Measures/policies

  • Closing schools
  • Stay-home rules for 65+ years old
  • Stay-home rules for 20- years old
  • Travel restrictions (regional and national)
  • Nation-wide lockdown
  • Closing businesses
  • Quarantine and isolation rules
  • Social distancing

These measures/restrictions change the time use of individuals.

We take into account quarantine and isolation rules and social distancing measures as well.

Module 4. Production and employment

  • Economic effect of policies
    • Businesses closures -> decline in production and employment
      • Decline in demand for inputs (backward links)
      • Decline in households demand (income effect)
        • Income support by the government
      • Decline in investment and exports
  • Use IO table to calculate these effects
    • For different categories of people (young/old, men/women, formal/informal, etc.)
    • For government finances (tax revenue - expenditures)

Parameter values

  • Publications
  • Calibration
    • Daily data on cases, deaths, and ICU numbers

Results

  • There is no trade off between economy and health (in the case of Covid-19)
  • Microsimulation is a useful tool
    • Which measures are effective?
    • What are the costs of measures?
    • Who are the most effected?
    • What could the government do?
